          "body": "Verse 9 is the psalm's most surprising claim: 'When God arose to judgment, to save all the humble of the earth.' The defeat of the armies and the silencing of the earth (76:8) are the precondition for the deliverance of the *anav* — the poor, the meek, the ones who had no cavalry, no shields, no stout hearts of their own. The same act that terrifies the powerful delivers the powerless. This is not incidental — Asaph makes it the *purpose* of the divine arising. God did not arise to demonstrate power for its own sake but to execute justice (*mishpat*, 76:9) on behalf of those who had no earthly advocate. This double edge of divine judgment — wrath toward the oppressor, salvation for the oppressed — runs throughout the Psalter (cf. Psalm 10:16-18; 68:4-5) and through the prophets (Isaiah 2:12-17; 61:1-2). Jesus quotes Isaiah 61:1 at the beginning of His ministry (Luke 4:18), identifying Himself as the one who fulfills God's judgment-pattern: the year of the LORD's favor is simultaneously the day of vengeance of our God. The humble who inherit the earth (Matthew 5:5) are the *anav* of Psalm 76:9."
