          "body": "Verse 10 is the psalm's most theologically dense line: 'For the wrath of man shall praise You; with a remnant of wrath You will gird Yourself.' This is not a promise that human anger will eventually calm down. It is the claim that God's sovereignty is so complete that even the most hostile force His enemies can marshal — *chemah*, burning, seething wrath — becomes, in His hands, an instrument of His own glorification. The first half of the verse names the mechanism: human wrath *shall praise* (*yadah*) God. The second half is almost comic in its confidence: whatever wrath remains after God has used it, He *girds Himself* with — puts on as a garment, a warrior's belt. Tim Keller notes that this is a uniquely biblical claim: not that God tolerates opposition but that He recruits it. The cross is the supreme instance — the wrath of Rome, the jealousy of the Sanhedrin, the betrayal of Judas, all co-opted into the atoning death that God had planned before the foundation of the world (Acts 2:23; 4:27-28). Psalm 76:10 is the doxological principle of which the cross is the definitive demonstration."
