          "body": "Having established who God is (76:1-10), the psalm turns in verse 11 to what that means for those who have witnessed it. The command is twofold and sequential: *make* vows and *fulfill* them. The making without the fulfilling is contempt dressed as piety. The vows in view are not emotional gestures made in crisis and forgotten in safety; they are covenant commitments — the formal renewal of allegiance by a community that has seen its God act on its behalf. The surrounding nations are also summoned to bring 'tribute' (*shay* — a gift of homage, the kind brought to a victorious king). And the closing verse (76:12) grounds the exhortation in the only argument that could make it compelling: He cuts off the spirit of princes. Even the most resolute human courage (*ruach* — spirit, the animating principle of resolve) is extinguished at His word. The psalm ends where it began — with the fear of God as the organizing center of reality. The congregation that has sung verses 1-10 arrives at verse 11 with no option but to respond: this God is too real, too sovereign, and too present to be acknowledged with anything less than renewed vows and fulfilled promises."
