        "title": "God is known at Zion — presence as power",
        "range": "76:1-3",
        "excerpt": "God is known in Judah; His name is great in Israel. His tabernacle is in Salem; His dwelling place also is in Zion. There He broke the flaming arrows, the shield and the sword and the weapons of war.",
        "body": "The psalm's opening strophe makes a tripartite claim: God is *known* in the covenant community, He is *present* in a specific place, and He has *acted* from that place against every weapon of war. These three claims are inseparable in Asaph's theology. The 'knowing' of verse 1 is not theological information but experiential recognition — *yada*, the same verb used for Adam knowing Eve (Genesis 4:1) and for Moses being known by God face to face (Deuteronomy 34:10). God is known in Judah because He has been encountered there in salvific acts. His name — the totality of His revealed character — is great because His deeds have declared it.\n\nThe dwelling-place language of verse 2 is deliberately dense. *Sokh* (tent, tabernacle) evokes the wilderness Tabernacle — the portable divine presence. *Meonah* (dwelling place) is elsewhere used for the lair of a lion (Amos 3:4; Nahum 2:12) — suggesting not a passive residence but the den of a predator who departs from it in pursuit. This is the same God who in verse 4 is 'more majestic than the mountains of prey' and whose dwelling in Zion makes the mountains of prey the lesser thing.\n\nVerse 3's 'there' (*sham*) is the pivot of the whole opening. The weapons were not broken because Israel fielded a superior army. They were broken *there* — at the place of divine habitation. The list — flaming arrows (*resheph*), shield (*magen*), sword (*cherev*), instruments of war — is comprehensive: every category of ancient offensive and defensive armament is accounted for. *Resheph* in other contexts is the name of a Canaanite deity of fire and plague; Asaph may be deliberately appropriating the name to insist that the 'divine fire' the nations feared was broken by Israel's God. Whatever the nations brought to Zion, they left without it.\n\nThis opening movement establishes the psalm's governing logic: divine presence is the cause; military outcome is the effect. The congregation does not need a larger army — it needs the living God dwelling in its midst. This theology is consummated in the New Testament when Jesus announces that He Himself is the temple that cannot be destroyed (John 2:19-21) and when the book of Revelation pictures the New Jerusalem as the place where God's tabernacle (*skēnē*) is permanently with man (Revelation 21:3).\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yada* (known, v.1) — experiential, relational knowing, not merely cognitive. *Meonah* (dwelling place, v.2) — the lair of a predator; used of God's 'den' in Psalm 90:1 and 91:9. *Resheph* (flaming arrows, v.3) — fiery bolts; possibly punning on the Canaanite fire-deity. *Shavar* (broke/shattered) — total destruction, not capture."
