        "excerpt": "For the wrath of man shall praise You; with a remnant of wrath You will gird Yourself.",
        "body": "Verse 10 is the psalm's most theologically concentrated statement and functions as the governing principle that makes everything in verses 1-9 intelligible. Asaph does not merely say that God *survived* human wrath or that God *overcame* human wrath. He says that human wrath *praises* God — becomes doxology — and that whatever wrath remains after God has finished with it, He wears as a warrior's belt. This is comprehensive divine sovereignty over opposition, stated in the most provocative terms available.\n\nThe structure of the verse is chiastic: wrath → shall praise You / with the remnant of wrath → You will gird Yourself. The first half names the mechanism (opposition becomes praise); the second half names what God does with the leftover (He equips Himself with it). The *chagar* (to gird) is the warrior's act of buckling on the sword-belt before battle. God girds Himself with the very residue of human hostility — He is not depleted by opposition but armed by it.\n\nHistorically, this verse describes precisely what happened when the Assyrian army fell: Sennacherib's arrogant boasting against YHWH (Isaiah 37:23-25 — 'By the power of my hand and by my wisdom I did this') became the occasion for YHWH's most dramatic self-display in the monarchic era. The wrath that came against Jerusalem turned to the praise of Israel's God, as the nations around observed what had happened. Isaiah 37:20 is the companion text: 'So that all the kingdoms of the earth may know that You alone, O LORD, are God.'\n\nCanonically, verse 10 anticipates what Peter announces at Pentecost (Acts 2:23): 'This Man, delivered over by the predetermined plan and foreknowledge of God, you nailed to a cross by the hands of godless men.' The greatest concentration of human *chemah* — the wrath of Rome, the hatred of the religious establishment, the abandonment of the disciples — was co-opted into the act of atonement that is the eternal praise of God. As Jonathan Edwards observed, the cross is the supreme instance of God's 'permitting sin for wise and holy ends.' The principle of Psalm 76:10 reaches its eschatological apex in Revelation 19:15, where the rider on the white horse treads the winepress of the wrath of God — wearing human opposition as His garment of victory.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chemah* (wrath) — burning heat, fury; appears twice in the verse, framing it. *Yadah* (shall praise) — the same root as 'Judah' (*Yehudah*) in verse 1, and as the standard thanksgiving vocabulary of the Psalter. *Sheerit chemah* (remnant of wrath) — what is left over after God has finished using it. *Chagar* (gird) — to buckle on a weapon-belt; the warrior's preparation for battle."
