        "number": 4,
        "title": "Make vows, bring tribute, fear the Cutter of princes",
        "range": "76:11-12",
        "excerpt": "Make vows to the LORD your God and fulfill them; let all who are around Him bring gifts to Him who is to be feared. He will cut off the spirit of princes; He is feared by the kings of the earth.",
        "body": "Having established the theological architecture — God dwells in Zion, He defeats every army with a word, He turns human wrath to praise — Asaph turns to demand. The imperative of verse 11 is directed at the covenant community ('your God' marks them as the specific addressees) but immediately widens: 'all who are around Him' — the surrounding peoples, the nations — are also summoned to bring *shay*, tribute, a gift of homage paid to a victorious sovereign. The psalm's universalism is genuine: the God who is known in Judah (76:1) is to be worshipped by the kings of the earth (76:12).\n\nThe vow-command is not peripheral. In Israel's worship, vows made in crisis and fulfilled in public assembly were a primary mechanism of covenant renewal (cf. Psalms 22:25; 50:14; 116:14-18). The community that has witnessed God's victory is expected to respond with formal, binding, fulfilled commitments — not vague emotional gratitude. The pairing of *nadar* (make vows) with *salem* (fulfill them) closes the loop: the vow that is never paid is the mark of a heart that was not truly changed by what it witnessed. Ecclesiastes 5:4-5 makes the same point with equal sharpness.\n\nThe closing verse (76:12) provides the ultimate warrant for both the making and the fulfilling: 'He will cut off the spirit of princes; He is feared by the kings of the earth.' The *batsar ruach nagid* — cutting off the spirit of princes — means extinguishing the courage, the resolution, the animating drive of the most powerful rulers. The word *nagid* (prince, leader) is used of the highest political-military authority. Even those figures are reduced to fearful subjects before Zion's God. If the kings of the earth fear Him, how much more should the covenant community — who know His name and have witnessed His acts — fear Him in worship?\n\nPeter Davids and Douglas Moo's observation (in their respective commentaries on New Testament texts drawing on Psalms) that the pattern of universal divine kingship in the Zion Psalms is fulfilled in the ascended Christ is directly applicable here. Ephesians 1:20-21 describes Christ as raised and seated 'far above all rule and authority and power and dominion' — the language of Psalm 76:12 applied to the Lord who cut off the spirit of every hostile power at the cross and empty tomb. Philippians 2:10-11 — 'every knee will bow and every tongue confess' — is the eschatological fulfillment of the summons of verse 11: all who are around Him, all the kings of the earth, will bring tribute to Him who is to be feared.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shay* (tribute, v.11) — a gift brought to a conquering king; used in Isaiah 18:7 for nations bringing tribute to YHWH on Zion. *Mora* (Him who is to be feared, v.11) — the noun form of *yare*, emphasizing the objective terribleness of God as the ground of worship. *Batsar* (cut off, v.12) — to clip, to harvest, to cut short; the spirit of the mightiest human leaders is harvested at God's pleasure."
